<p>HereŌĆÖs the thing: none of that extra work was failure. The model wasnŌĆÖt broken. I wasnŌĆÖt prompting badly. Things got done. But the session data told a different story than ŌĆ£productive.ŌĆØ It told the story of how much invisible work hides inside every AI workflow ŌĆö and why weŌĆÖve never had a name for it before.</p>

<h2 id="most-people-measure-the-wrong-thing">Most people measure the wrong thing</h2>

<p>When we talk about AI productivity, we measure outputs. Did the task complete? How fast? How many tokens did it cost?</p>

<p>These are real metrics. But they miss the layer underneath.</p>

<p>Think about what actually happens in a coding session with an AI. You describe a task. The model responds with something close to what you meant ŌĆö but not quite. You correct it. It adjusts. You verify the result, notice a filename doesnŌĆÖt match, fix the reference, check the directory, confirm the output.</p>

<p>At every step, you are both <em>doing the task</em> and <em>negotiating shared context</em>. The task work and the alignment work happen simultaneously, and almost nobody tracks them separately.</p>

<p>IŌĆÖve started calling the second kind <em>alignment tax</em>: the extra cycles spent not on the work itself, but on establishing the shared reality the work requires.</p>

<p>Alignment tax is not a bug. ItŌĆÖs not even avoidable. ItŌĆÖs a structural feature of how language models and humans collaborate. The model has no persistent memory of your project. It doesnŌĆÖt know your file naming conventions, your aesthetic preferences, or that you named the file <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">context_window.svg</code> with an underscore. You know all of that. The model knows none of it until you tell it ŌĆö and you often donŌĆÖt know you need to tell it until it guesses wrong.</p>

<p>What Tapes does is make this visible. Not to shame you for it. To help you see it clearly so you can work with it deliberately.</p>

<h2 id="let-me-show-you-what-i-mean">Let me show you what I mean</h2>

<p>HereŌĆÖs a moment from my actual session. I asked the model to place images in a blog post. Simple task. The model created placeholder image paths ŌĆö reasonable defaults ŌĆö and completed the task.</p>

<p>Then I uploaded the real files.</p>

<p>The model had written <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ai-llms-models.svg</code>. The actual filename was <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ai-llms-model.svg</code>. One character difference. The model had written <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">context-window.svg</code>. The actual filename was <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">context_window.svg</code>. A dash versus an underscore.</p>

<p>The task was technically done twice: once with placeholder filenames, once with real ones. The second pass was alignment work ŌĆö reconciling what the model assumed against what actually existed on disk.</p>

<p>Neither pass was a failure. The session felt smooth in the moment. I didnŌĆÖt notice the overhead.</p>

