<p>When I went back and looked at the session data, I could see the shape of it: <em>intent ŌåÆ inspect ŌåÆ adjust ŌåÆ retry ŌåÆ continue</em>. Not a straight line from task to output. A loop. And the loop wasnŌĆÖt random. It had a structure. It always closed on the same gap: the gap between what the model assumed and what was true.</p>

<h2 id="three-kinds-of-alignment-work">Three kinds of alignment work</h2>

<p>After spending time in this session data, I started to see patterns. Alignment tax doesnŌĆÖt show up as one thing. It shows up as three:</p>

<p><strong>Semantic alignment</strong> is when the model and you are using the same words to mean different things. In my session, the biggest instance of this was visual: I said ŌĆ£sparklesŌĆØ and meant blurry glowing halos like stars. The model implemented tiny 1ŌĆō2px dots ŌĆö technically sparkles, but invisible at that size. The word ŌĆ£sparkleŌĆØ carried different visual assumptions on each side of the conversation. Three full iteration cycles happened before we landed on the same image.</p>

<p><strong>Structural alignment</strong> is when you and the model have different maps of the territory. I asked the model to find files in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">documents/ai blogpost</code>. The model didnŌĆÖt have access to that directory. Neither of us knew that until the model tried. Structural alignment failures are easy to fix ŌĆö once you know the layout mismatch exists. The cost is the discovery.</p>

<p><strong>State alignment</strong> is the ongoing work of keeping the model current as reality changes. The blog post images I uploaded had different names than the placeholders. The database filename changed from <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">tapes.db</code> to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">tapes.sqlite</code>. Every time the ground truth shifted, there was alignment work to sync the modelŌĆÖs working assumptions. This isnŌĆÖt a bug in the model. ItŌĆÖs a consequence of having no persistent memory.</p>

