<p>In my session, visual design tasks had the highest alignment tax by far. Describing what I wanted an interactive component to <em>look like</em> ŌĆö in words, to a model ŌĆö generated more correction cycles than any purely technical task. Renaming a file across a codebase: low alignment tax. Building CSS effects from a reference image: high alignment tax.</p>

<p>ThatŌĆÖs useful to know. Not because it changes what I work on, but because it changes how I work on it. When I know a task category carries high alignment overhead, I can front-load the alignment work ŌĆö share the reference image first, establish the visual vocabulary explicitly, describe what I <em>donŌĆÖt</em> want alongside what I do.</p>

<p>The developers who get the most out of AI tools arenŌĆÖt necessarily the best prompters. TheyŌĆÖre the ones whoŌĆÖve learned to recognize alignment work for what it is, and front-load it.</p>

<h2 id="what-tapes-actually-records">What Tapes actually records</h2>

<p>Tapes runs as a wrapper around Claude Code: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">tapes start claude</code>. It captures the entire CLI session at the process level, writing to a local SQLite database in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">~/.tapes/</code>. Every message, every model response, every token count, every timestamp.</p>

<p>What this gives you:</p>

<ul>
  <li>A complete, searchable record of what happened in the session</li>
