<p>That last one matters more than it sounds. Working in an AI session, youŌĆÖre inside it. Things feel smooth or rough in real time. You donŌĆÖt have the vantage point to see the shape of the whole thing. Tapes gives you that vantage point afterward.</p>

<p>I didnŌĆÖt know IŌĆÖd spent three full cycles trying to communicate ŌĆ£sparkles that look like stars, not dustŌĆØ until I looked at the session data. In the moment, it felt like iteration. In the data, it looked like a pattern ŌĆö and patterns are solvable.</p>

<h2 id="the-uncomfortable-truth-about-productive">The uncomfortable truth about ŌĆ£productiveŌĆØ</h2>

<p>WeŌĆÖve borrowed ŌĆ£productiveŌĆØ from a world where the work was legible. You wrote code, it compiled or it didnŌĆÖt. You finished the feature, you didnŌĆÖt. Productivity meant output per unit of time.</p>

<p>AI sessions scramble that. The work is less legible. Alignment work looks like task work from the outside ŌĆö youŌĆÖre still sending messages, getting responses, moving forward. But the alignment work isnŌĆÖt moving the task forward. ItŌĆÖs maintaining the conditions under which the task can move forward.</p>

<p>This is new. We donŌĆÖt have great vocabulary for it yet. We donŌĆÖt have metrics. Most AI productivity conversations are still about prompting quality, model capability, and output speed ŌĆö none of which touch the alignment layer.</p>

<p>Tapes is one of the first tools IŌĆÖve seen that makes the alignment layer visible. Not through theory. Through data from your actual sessions.</p>

